issue.title: Provide an option to disable -*withBlob- for a specific table
issue.body: In our db model we have a table containing several column with `varbinary(4)`. This binaries are required and the generated object isn't valid without them.  I have disabled the generation of separate blob models with `<context defaultModelType="flat">`. In this scenario I would like to disable all `*withBlobs` methods for a specific table, too. Otherwise it would be miss leading and the generation of an invalid object would be possible.

comment.body:
It looks like you are using the older deprecated runtime `<context targetRuntime="MyBatis3">`. In the newer runtimes, the model type is always flat, and there are no separate "WithBlobs" methods (and the generated code is much better too!). So you might try the newer runtime and see if it's closer to what you want.

In the old runtime, you could write a simple plugin that disables the "WithBlobs" methods. If you do that, then you won't be able to access the BLOB fields. So I'm wondering if you want to also change the non-blobs methods so that they include all columns. For example, "updateByPrimaryKeyWithBlobs" is disabled and "updateByPrimaryKey" is changed to include all columns. You could also do that in a plugin, but it is more complex (you could disable "updateByPrimaryKey", then rename "updateByPrimaryKeyWithBlobls" -> "updateByPrimaryKey").

issue.title: Add `affectData` attribute to `@Select`, `@SelectProvider` and `<select />`
issue.body:
Some DBs support returning result set from INSERT/UPDATE/DELETE statements. e.g.

- PostgreSQL has `RETURNING`
- MS SQL Server has `OUTPUT`

By using `@Select`, `@SelectProvider` or `<select />`, it is possible to retrieve data from those statements.
The problem is that calling `SqlSession#commit()` or `SqlSession#rollback()`does not work as expected because MyBatis assumes SELECT does not affect DB data [1].

By setting `affectData=true`, users can indicate that the SELECT statement affects DB data.

Related to:

- #1189
- #2156 
- #2363 
- https://groups.google.com/g/mybatis-user/c/1Wn-0IyUi-Q/m/2MUAL4nFBwAJ

Notes:

- The use of `@Select`, `@SelectProvider`, `<select />` might look unintuitive, but changing the INSERT/UPDATE/DELETE behavior requires bigger change. The characteristic of these statement is closer to SELECT from MyBatis' perspective.
- Enabling `affectData` does not automatically activate `flushCache`.

TODO: doc

@emacarron @jeffgbutler @mnesarco @hazendaz  @kazuki43zoo @eddumelendez 
Any input would be appreciated!

[1] An obvious (but not ideal) workaround is to execute another INSERT/UPDATE/DELETE in the same session.

comment.body:
I thought about just having a single `@Statement` too! But you are correct about the tradeoffs and difficulties. The problem of returning rows affected and/or a mapped result from an update is difficult to overcome in Java.

Spring JDBC template basically has four methods: `query`, `update`, `batchUpdate`, and `execute`. I believe normal usage there would be to use `query` for an `insert ... returning`. So they have the same issue we have.

Your idea is the least intrusive for sure. I'm +1 on your implementation.

comment.body:
@harawata I'm happy you are working on this issue! Your solution makes sense to me, but I wonder if it will cause too much confusion as statements will be written like this:

```xml
<select ...>
  UPDATE...
</select>
```

I think users are sometimes confused about this thinking that `<select>` means more than it actually does. For us it means "don't dirty the session and do look for a result set", but users sometimes think it forces an actual SELECT statement.

I wonder if it would ultimately be less confusing to add resultSet support to `<insert>`, `<update>`, and `<delete>`? I know you said it is a bigger change, but those three tags are essentially the same under the covers - so maybe it isn't so bad. The main thing you have to reason about is the correct order of processing generated keys and resultSets.

issue.title: Why not support having?
issue.body:
Is there any details why not support ‘having’?

And how to extend ‘Mybatis Dynamic SQL’ to support having?

pull_request.title: Add "having" Support to Select Statements
pull_request.body:
This PR adds support for "having" clauses in select statements. The PR includes a refactoring of the "where" support so we can reuse the and/or logic and rendering that is already present in the "where" clause support. This because "having" and "where" are essentially the same.

One slight behavior change with this refactoring is that the renderer will now remove a useless open/close parentheses around certain rendered where clauses. Previously it was possible to have a rendered where clause like this:

```sql
where (a < 2 and b > 3)
```

The renderer will now remove the open/close parentheses in a case like this.

The "having" support is not as full featured as the "where" support in that we don't support independent and reusable having clauses, and we don't support composable having functions. If you have a reasonable use case for that kind of support, please let us know.

In the Java DSL, a "having" clause can only be coded after a "group by" clause - which is a reasonable restriction as "having" is only needed if there is a "group by".

In the Kotlin DSL, the "group by" restriction is not present because of the free form nature of that DSL - but you should probably only use "having" if there is a "group by". Also note that the freestanding "and" and "or" functions in the Kotlin DSL still only apply to the where clause.

Resolves #418

issue.title: Provide an option to disable -*withBlob- for a specific table
issue.body: In our db model we have a table containing several column with `varbinary(4)`. This binaries are required and the generated object isn't valid without them.  I have disabled the generation of separate blob models with `<context defaultModelType="flat">`. In this scenario I would like to disable all `*withBlobs` methods for a specific table, too. Otherwise it would be miss leading and the generation of an invalid object would be possible.

comment.body:
It looks like you are using the older deprecated runtime `<context targetRuntime="MyBatis3">`. In the newer runtimes, the model type is always flat, and there are no separate "WithBlobs" methods (and the generated code is much better too!). So you might try the newer runtime and see if it's closer to what you want.

In the old runtime, you could write a simple plugin that disables the "WithBlobs" methods. If you do that, then you won't be able to access the BLOB fields. So I'm wondering if you want to also change the non-blobs methods so that they include all columns. For example, "updateByPrimaryKeyWithBlobs" is disabled and "updateByPrimaryKey" is changed to include all columns. You could also do that in a plugin, but it is more complex (you could disable "updateByPrimaryKey", then rename "updateByPrimaryKeyWithBlobls" -> "updateByPrimaryKey").

issue.title: Add `affectData` attribute to `@Select`, `@SelectProvider` and `<select />`
issue.body:
Some DBs support returning result set from INSERT/UPDATE/DELETE statements. e.g.

- PostgreSQL has `RETURNING`
- MS SQL Server has `OUTPUT`

By using `@Select`, `@SelectProvider` or `<select />`, it is possible to retrieve data from those statements.
The problem is that calling `SqlSession#commit()` or `SqlSession#rollback()`does not work as expected because MyBatis assumes SELECT does not affect DB data [1].

By setting `affectData=true`, users can indicate that the SELECT statement affects DB data.

Related to:

- #1189
- #2156 
- #2363 
- https://groups.google.com/g/mybatis-user/c/1Wn-0IyUi-Q/m/2MUAL4nFBwAJ

Notes:

- The use of `@Select`, `@SelectProvider`, `<select />` might look unintuitive, but changing the INSERT/UPDATE/DELETE behavior requires bigger change. The characteristic of these statement is closer to SELECT from MyBatis' perspective.
- Enabling `affectData` does not automatically activate `flushCache`.

TODO: doc

@emacarron @jeffgbutler @mnesarco @hazendaz  @kazuki43zoo @eddumelendez 
Any input would be appreciated!

[1] An obvious (but not ideal) workaround is to execute another INSERT/UPDATE/DELETE in the same session.

comment.body:
I thought about just having a single `@Statement` too! But you are correct about the tradeoffs and difficulties. The problem of returning rows affected and/or a mapped result from an update is difficult to overcome in Java.

Spring JDBC template basically has four methods: `query`, `update`, `batchUpdate`, and `execute`. I believe normal usage there would be to use `query` for an `insert ... returning`. So they have the same issue we have.

Your idea is the least intrusive for sure. I'm +1 on your implementation.

comment.body:
@harawata I'm happy you are working on this issue! Your solution makes sense to me, but I wonder if it will cause too much confusion as statements will be written like this:

```xml
<select ...>
  UPDATE...
</select>
```

I think users are sometimes confused about this thinking that `<select>` means more than it actually does. For us it means "don't dirty the session and do look for a result set", but users sometimes think it forces an actual SELECT statement.

I wonder if it would ultimately be less confusing to add resultSet support to `<insert>`, `<update>`, and `<delete>`? I know you said it is a bigger change, but those three tags are essentially the same under the covers - so maybe it isn't so bad. The main thing you have to reason about is the correct order of processing generated keys and resultSets.

issue.title: Why not support having?
issue.body:
Is there any details why not support ‘having’?

And how to extend ‘Mybatis Dynamic SQL’ to support having?

pull_request.title: Add "having" Support to Select Statements
pull_request.body:
This PR adds support for "having" clauses in select statements. The PR includes a refactoring of the "where" support so we can reuse the and/or logic and rendering that is already present in the "where" clause support. This because "having" and "where" are essentially the same.

One slight behavior change with this refactoring is that the renderer will now remove a useless open/close parentheses around certain rendered where clauses. Previously it was possible to have a rendered where clause like this:

```sql
where (a < 2 and b > 3)
```

The renderer will now remove the open/close parentheses in a case like this.

The "having" support is not as full featured as the "where" support in that we don't support independent and reusable having clauses, and we don't support composable having functions. If you have a reasonable use case for that kind of support, please let us know.

In the Java DSL, a "having" clause can only be coded after a "group by" clause - which is a reasonable restriction as "having" is only needed if there is a "group by".

In the Kotlin DSL, the "group by" restriction is not present because of the free form nature of that DSL - but you should probably only use "having" if there is a "group by". Also note that the freestanding "and" and "or" functions in the Kotlin DSL still only apply to the where clause.

Resolves #418

issue.title: Provide an option to disable -*withBlob- for a specific table
issue.body: In our db model we have a table containing several column with `varbinary(4)`. This binaries are required and the generated object isn't valid without them.  I have disabled the generation of separate blob models with `<context defaultModelType="flat">`. In this scenario I would like to disable all `*withBlobs` methods for a specific table, too. Otherwise it would be miss leading and the generation of an invalid object would be possible.

comment.body:
It looks like you are using the older deprecated runtime `<context targetRuntime="MyBatis3">`. In the newer runtimes, the model type is always flat, and there are no separate "WithBlobs" methods (and the generated code is much better too!). So you might try the newer runtime and see if it's closer to what you want.

In the old runtime, you could write a simple plugin that disables the "WithBlobs" methods. If you do that, then you won't be able to access the BLOB fields. So I'm wondering if you want to also change the non-blobs methods so that they include all columns. For example, "updateByPrimaryKeyWithBlobs" is disabled and "updateByPrimaryKey" is changed to include all columns. You could also do that in a plugin, but it is more complex (you could disable "updateByPrimaryKey", then rename "updateByPrimaryKeyWithBlobls" -> "updateByPrimaryKey").

issue.title: Add `affectData` attribute to `@Select`, `@SelectProvider` and `<select />`
issue.body:
Some DBs support returning result set from INSERT/UPDATE/DELETE statements. e.g.

- PostgreSQL has `RETURNING`
- MS SQL Server has `OUTPUT`

By using `@Select`, `@SelectProvider` or `<select />`, it is possible to retrieve data from those statements.
The problem is that calling `SqlSession#commit()` or `SqlSession#rollback()`does not work as expected because MyBatis assumes SELECT does not affect DB data [1].

By setting `affectData=true`, users can indicate that the SELECT statement affects DB data.

Related to:

- #1189
- #2156 
- #2363 
- https://groups.google.com/g/mybatis-user/c/1Wn-0IyUi-Q/m/2MUAL4nFBwAJ

Notes:

- The use of `@Select`, `@SelectProvider`, `<select />` might look unintuitive, but changing the INSERT/UPDATE/DELETE behavior requires bigger change. The characteristic of these statement is closer to SELECT from MyBatis' perspective.
- Enabling `affectData` does not automatically activate `flushCache`.

TODO: doc

@emacarron @jeffgbutler @mnesarco @hazendaz  @kazuki43zoo @eddumelendez 
Any input would be appreciated!

[1] An obvious (but not ideal) workaround is to execute another INSERT/UPDATE/DELETE in the same session.

comment.body:
I thought about just having a single `@Statement` too! But you are correct about the tradeoffs and difficulties. The problem of returning rows affected and/or a mapped result from an update is difficult to overcome in Java.

Spring JDBC template basically has four methods: `query`, `update`, `batchUpdate`, and `execute`. I believe normal usage there would be to use `query` for an `insert ... returning`. So they have the same issue we have.

Your idea is the least intrusive for sure. I'm +1 on your implementation.

comment.body:
@harawata I'm happy you are working on this issue! Your solution makes sense to me, but I wonder if it will cause too much confusion as statements will be written like this:

```xml
<select ...>
  UPDATE...
</select>
```

I think users are sometimes confused about this thinking that `<select>` means more than it actually does. For us it means "don't dirty the session and do look for a result set", but users sometimes think it forces an actual SELECT statement.

issue.title: Why not support having?
issue.body:
Is there any details why not support ‘having’?

And how to extend ‘Mybatis Dynamic SQL’ to support having?

pull_request.title: Add "having" Support to Select Statements
pull_request.body:
This PR adds support for "having" clauses in select statements. The PR includes a refactoring of the "where" support so we can reuse the and/or logic and rendering that is already present in the "where" clause support. This because "having" and "where" are essentially the same.

One slight behavior change with this refactoring is that the renderer will now remove a useless open/close parentheses around certain rendered where clauses. Previously it was possible to have a rendered where clause like this:

```sql
where (a < 2 and b > 3)
```

The renderer will now remove the open/close parentheses in a case like this.

The "having" support is not as full featured as the "where" support in that we don't support independent and reusable having clauses, and we don't support composable having functions. If you have a reasonable use case for that kind of support, please let us know.

In the Java DSL, a "having" clause can only be coded after a "group by" clause - which is a reasonable restriction as "having" is only needed if there is a "group by".

In the Kotlin DSL, the "group by" restriction is not present because of the free form nature of that DSL - but you should probably only use "having" if there is a "group by". Also note that the freestanding "and" and "or" functions in the Kotlin DSL still only apply to the where clause.

Resolves #418
